Jenni Evans, News24Dr Ben Ngubane in Parliament. (File, Thulani Gqirana, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; Ben Ngubane, the Eskom chairperson has resigned with immediate effect, Minister of Public Enterprises, Lynne Brown said on Monday.&ldquo;Dr Ngubane formally tendered his resignation, which I accepted,&rdquo; Brown, said in a statement.Ngubane has been named twice so far in the GuptaLeaks saga. Once due to a failed bid to secure a lucrative oil concession in the Central African Republic (CAR) as well as in the revelations about the capture of Eskom.&ldquo;I would like to thank Dr Ngubane for his contribution to turning Eskom around since the load shedding days of 2014/15, and wish him well in the future.&ldquo;To ensure continuity at Eskom, I have decided to appoint Mr Zethembe Khoza as interim chairperson until I am able to take new board appointments to Cabinet for approval,&rdquo; Brown said.Eskom&rsquo;s Annual General Meeting is scheduled to take place later this month.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.